Diabetes¶

In this dataset you have 3 different outputs:

  1. No readmission;
  2. A readmission in less than 30 days (this situation is not good, because maybe your treatment was not appropriate);
  3. A readmission in more than 30 days (this one is not so good as well the last one, however, the reason could be the state of the patient.
    Your task is either to classify a patient-hospital outcome or to cluster them aiming at finding patterns that give a distinct insight.

This is a multiclass problem, where we are trying to predict 3 outputs. In aditional of the multiclas algorithm we will discover the features that has more impact in the prediction

All libraries are imported here:

2. Data Cleaning and Feature Engineering¶

It is hard to do feature engineering if we have no knowledge about the dataset. It is important to communicate with an expert to do the best preprocessing to different features. In this case we will only do one hot encoding and binary transformation. It's important that the number of observations is bigger than the number of features.

# Generate dummies for every column and append
for column in columns:

    df = pd.concat([df, one_hot], axis=1)

#Function to count null values depending on null indicator
def check_null(df:pd.DataFrame, column:str, indicator:list):
    for i in indicator:
        count = df[column][df[column] == i].count()
        print(column, count, f'{round(count/len(df)*100)}%', f'indicator = {i}')

2.3 Diagnosis preprocessing¶

Original Diabetes Paper

  • Diagnosis 1 Nominal The primary diagnosis (coded as first three digits of ICD9); 848 distinct values

  • Diagnosis 2 Nominal Secondary diagnosis (coded as first three digits of ICD9); 923 distinct values

  • Diagnosis 3 Nominal Additional secondary diagnosis (coded as first three digits of ICD9); 954 distinct values

    • diag 1-3 are string values, we should change them to numeric type

    It is extremely hard to include every different diagnosis in the model, therefore, based on the anbstract of the paper I decided only to use the primary diagnosis.

    In [281]:
    # Dropping columns
df = df.drop(columns = ['diag_2', 'diag_3'])

    In [282]:
    # Create new columns
df['Circulatory'] = 0
df['Respiratory'] = 0
df['Digestive'] = 0
df['Diabetes'] = 0
df['Injury'] = 0
df['Musculoskeletal'] = 0
df['Genitourinary'] = 0
df['Neoplasms'] = 0
df['Other'] = 0

# Transform EV to number
df.loc[df['diag_1'].str.contains('V'), ['diag_1']] = '0'
df.loc[df['diag_1'].str.contains('E'), ['diag_1']] = '0'

# convert column to numeric
df["diag_1"] = pd.to_numeric(df["diag_1"])
    In [283]:
    # Fill column based on icd9 codes
for idx, obs in df.iterrows():
    if (obs['diag_1'] >= 390 and obs['diag_1'] <= 459) or obs['diag_1'] == 785:
        df.loc[idx, 'Circulatory'] = 1
        
    elif (obs['diag_1'] >= 460 and obs['diag_1'] <= 519) or obs['diag_1'] == 786:
        df.loc[idx, 'Respiratory'] = 1
        
    elif (obs['diag_1'] >= 520 and obs['diag_1'] <= 579) or obs['diag_1'] == 787:
        df.loc[idx, 'Digestive'] = 1
        
    elif obs['diag_1'] == 250:
        df.loc[idx, 'Diabetes'] = 1
        
    elif obs['diag_1'] >= 800 and obs['diag_1'] <= 999:
        df.loc[idx, 'Injury'] = 1
        
    elif obs['diag_1'] >= 710 and obs['diag_1'] <= 739:
        df.loc[idx, 'Musculoskeletal'] = 1   
        
    elif (obs['diag_1'] >= 580 and obs['diag_1'] <= 629) or obs['diag_1'] == 788:
        df.loc[idx, 'Genitourinary'] = 1
    
    elif obs['diag_1'] >= 140 and obs['diag_1'] <= 239:
        df.loc[idx, 'Neoplasms'] = 1
    
    else:
        df.loc[idx, 'Other'] = 1

    4.2 Classifiers¶

    For this statistical modelling I am going to test Logistic Regression, KNN, Naive Bayes, Linear and RBF SVM, Decision Trees, Random Forest, Quadratic Discriminant Analysis and a Multi-layer perceptron

    In [291]:
    from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, recall_score, precision_score, f1_score, confusion_matrix
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold, GridSearchCV, RandomizedSearchCV
import warnings; warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
from matplotlib.colors import ListedColormap
from sklearn import metrics
    In [295]:
    def run_classifier(clf, param_grid, title):
    # -----------------------------------------------------
    cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits= 3, shuffle = True, random_state= 123)
    
    # Randomized grid search
    n_iter_search = 1
    gs = RandomizedSearchCV(clf, 
                            param_distributions = param_grid,
                            n_iter = n_iter_search, 
                            cv = cv, 
                            scoring= 'accuracy')
    # -----------------------------------------------------
    # Train model
    gs.fit(x_train, y_train)  
    print("The best parameters are %s" % (gs.best_params_)) 
    
    # Predict on test set
    y_pred = gs.best_estimator_.predict(x_test)
    
    # Get Probability estimates
    y_prob = gs.best_estimator_.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1]
    # -----------------------------------------------------
    print('Accuracy score: %.2f%%' %(accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)*100))  
    print('Precision score: %.2f%%' % (precision_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted')*100))
    print('Recall score: %.2f%%' % (recall_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted')*100))
    print('F1 score: %.2f%%' % (f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted')*100))
    # -----------------------------------------------------
    # Plot confusion matrix
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)#, labels= target_names)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True, cbar = False, fmt = "d", linewidths = .5, cmap = "Blues", ax = ax)
    ax.set_title("Confusion Matrix")
    ax.set_xlabel("Predicted class")
    ax.set_ylabel("Actual class")
    fig.tight_layout()
    
    if title == 'Random Forest' or  title =='Decision Tree' or  title =='XGBoost':
        # Create list of top most features based on importance
        feature_names = x_train.columns
        feature_imports = gs.best_estimator_.feature_importances_
        most_imp_features = pd.DataFrame([f for f in zip(feature_names,feature_imports)], columns=["Feature", "Importance"]).nlargest(10, "Importance")
        most_imp_features.sort_values(by="Importance", inplace=True)
        plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
        plt.barh(range(len(most_imp_features)), most_imp_features.Importance, align='center', alpha=0.8)
        plt.yticks(range(len(most_imp_features)), most_imp_features.Feature, fontsize=14)
        plt.xlabel('Importance')
        plt.title(f'Most important features - {title} ')
        plt.show()

    Conclusions¶

    The results after balancing the data are not very different from the original ones, but they do increase mainly in the neural networks. The variable that is repeated the most to make the prediction is the number of patient visits. This being a decisive factor for predictions.

    It was attempted to predict for a binary output in which the patients who returned to the hospital after 30 days or who did not return were combined against those who returned before, but the class imbalance produced bad results.

    During the processing, new techniques could be used to speed up the training, such as pca or normalize the data.

    It could also help training more models with more hyperparameter tunning.

    Support from medical experts is required to improve feature engineering.
